-- 
Dubai Shares Advance on Optimism Europe Crisis Will Be Contained

-- B y   Z a h r a   H a n k i r
-- 
2011-10-11T08:31:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-11/dubai-shares-advance-on-optimism-europe-crisis-will-be-contained.html
Dubai’s shares gained for the third
time in four days as optimism European policy makers will
contain the region’s debt crisis bolstered demand for emerging-
market assets.  Arabtec Holding Co. (ARTC) , the United Arab Emirates’ biggest
construction company, climbed 2.3 percent and  Emaar Properties
PJSC (EMAAR) , the developer of the world’s tallest tower, rose 1.2
percent. The  DFM General Index (DFMGI)  gained 0.7 percent to 1,398.85 at
11:43 a.m. in Dubai. About 21 million shares traded in Dubai
today, compared with this year’s daily average of 110 million
shares. The  Bloomberg GCC 200 Index (BGCC200)  advanced 0.2 percent.  U.S. stocks rallied yesterday, with the  S&P 500  advancing
3.4 percent, after German Chancellor  Angela Merkel  and French
President Nicholas Sarkozy pledged over the weekend to deliver a
plan to recapitalize the  Europe ’s banks and address  Greece ’s
debt crisis by Nov. 3. The STOXX Europe 600 Index rose 1.7
percent yesterday before slipping 0.9 percent today as investors
awaited a vote in Slovakia on the euro-area bailout fund.  “The Dubai financial market is taking cues from
international markets but in low volumes,” said Samer Darwiche,
a financial analyst at Gulfmena Investments in Dubai.  Emerging-market equities rose today as Chinese lenders
surged after a state-owned  investment company  bought bank shares
and Japanese equities climbed on resuming trade from a holiday.
The MSCI Asia Pacific Index gained 1.8 percent.  Arabtec advanced to as high as 1.33 dirhams. Emaar added
0.8 percent to 2.57 dirhams.  Kuwait’s measure advanced 0.1 percent, Abu Dhabi’s  ADX
General Index (ADSMI)  gained 0.2 percent and Qatar’s  QE Index (DSM)  rose 0.6
percent. Bahrain’s BB All Share Index climbed 0.1 percent.
Oman’s  MSM30 Index (MSM30)  was little changed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
